Run one sweep of the live <PROJECT> bug/feature tracker. This command is
designed to run unattended (manually, via `/loop`, or on a cron schedule)
-- don't block on interactive confirmation; when something needs a human
call, leave it open with a note instead of guessing.

## 1. Fetch open reports

See `../INTAKE.md` for the full read/write contract. `scope=bugs` alone
defaults to `type=bug` -- feature requests don't come back unless you ask
explicitly with `type=feature` or `type=all`. That's deliberate: the bug
queue is only things that must eventually be fixed or explicitly
reclassified out, not a mixed backlog of defects and ideas.

```
curl -sL "<TRACKER_URL>?scope=bugs&status=open&limit=50"
```

Each report has `{timestamp, name, url, description, status, note, type}`.
`url` is often a deep link into the app -- open it in context if the
description alone isn't enough to understand the bug.

## 2. Triage every report into exactly one bucket

- **Mechanical fix** -- a concrete, reproducible defect with an
  unambiguous correct behavior, verifiable in this sandbox (this
  project's own test suite, or a throwaway local harness).
- **Actually a feature idea, not a bug** -- reclassify (step 5) rather
  than leaving it in the bug queue with a note. The feature backlog isn't
  held to "must eventually resolve," so it's the right place for
  open-ended ideas to sit.
- **Needs a human call, but is a real bug** -- genuine defect, but the fix
  isn't obvious, can't be verified in this sandbox, or the right fix
  requires a design decision only the user can make. Stays open, with a
  note. Different from the next bucket: this one needs a person's
  judgment, not just more time.
- **Real bug, but too big for this sweep -- hand off to nightly** -- a
  genuine, fixable-by-an-agent defect where the fix is straightforward in
  principle but needs more investigation/build time than a fast, frequent
  sweep should spend. Leave it open with a note prefixed exactly
  `NIGHTLY:` (nightly-batch.md's own fetch step looks for this prefix and
  treats it as in-scope automatically, regardless of FOCUS.md's stated
  focus -- see that file):
  ```
  curl -sL "<TRACKER_URL>" -X POST -H "Content-Type: text/plain" \
    --data-raw '{"type":"resolve","timestamp":"<exact timestamp string>","status":"open","note":"NIGHTLY: <what makes this too big for a sweep, and what a real fix looks like>"}'
  ```
- **Duplicate of an already-tracked issue** -- matches an existing code
  comment/README TODO entry covering the same ground.

Don't resolve a design/feature-idea report as "fixed" on your own
judgment. Reclassify a feature idea rather than building it here -- not
because it needs the user's OK (FOCUS.md's autonomy policy says
otherwise), but because this tier stays fast and narrow on purpose;
`/nightly-batch` is where feature ideas actually get built.

## 3. Implement each mechanical fix

Locate the relevant code. Write or extend a regression test if the
project has a test suite. **Verify the test actually catches the bug**:
temporarily revert the fix, confirm the new test fails, then reapply and
confirm it passes -- a test that passes both ways isn't proving anything.

## 4. Commit

One commit per sweep (or several if the fixes are unrelated enough to
tell apart in history). Short imperative summary line, a body explaining
*why* each fix matters, not just what changed.

## 5. Update the tracker

For each report fixed, mark it resolved, referencing the commit hash (see
`../INTAKE.md` for the exact POST shape). Reclassify a feature idea filed
as a bug instead of resolving/noting it in place. Leave a genuine
needs-a-human bug open with a note on what a real fix would require.

**Gotcha**: never trust the raw HTTP response from a POST here -- see
`../INTAKE.md`. Always confirm by re-fetching afterward.

## 6. Record this sweep's status

If this project's tracker backend supports the `sweep-status` contract
(see `../INTAKE.md`) -- every run posts this, even one that fixed
nothing, so a live status readout has proof the sweep is still running
instead of only a log nobody's watching:

```
curl -sL "<TRACKER_URL>" -X POST -H "Content-Type: text/plain" \
  --data-raw '{"type":"sweep-status","fetched":<N>,"fixed":<F>,"reclassified":<R>,"leftOpen":<L>}'
```

If the project's backend doesn't have this yet, skip this step and note
in the summary that it's a gap (don't add the backend support
unilaterally in the middle of a routine sweep).

## 7. Flag anything that needs the user's own judgment

If anything this sweep touched genuinely needs a decision only the user
can make -- bigger than one report's "needs a human call" note (step 2):
an ambiguous policy question, a real tradeoff, a "which of these two
directions" fork -- append it to `.claude/QUESTIONS.md` at the repo root
(create with a one-line header if it doesn't exist). Append only, never
overwrite or trim existing entries. Format: `- **YYYY-MM-DD (bug-sweep):
<question>**` + short context, then a `  > (answer inline here)`
placeholder line so the user's reply slot is obvious. Most sweeps have
nothing to add here; don't manufacture a question just to have an entry.

Answer-processing is the **nightly's** job, not this sweep's. The user
replies inline under a question with a `> ` line (QUESTIONS.md's header
documents it); `/nightly-batch` reads those, acts, and clears them. This
fast 15-minute loop must NOT act on or delete a `> ` answer itself --
leave answered questions in place for the nightly, so the two tiers never
race over the file.

## 8. Report a summary

Start with the exact heading `## Summary` (not a variant -- this run is
logged alongside every other run, unattended, and a consistent heading is
what makes the log grep-able later) and one compact result line directly
under it:

```
Fetched: N (M new) · Fixed & pushed: F · Reclassified: R · Handed to nightly: H · Left open: L
```

Below that, in prose: what got fixed and committed, what got reclassified
as a feature (and why), what got handed off to nightly (and why), what
got a note-only bug left open, how many new reports came in since last
sweep, and whether anything got appended to `.claude/QUESTIONS.md`. Don't
resolve, reclassify, or hand off more than a handful of reports in one
sweep without flagging anything that felt like a judgment call, even if
you didn't block on it.
